[[File:Earth-crust-cutaway-numbered.svg|thumb|250px|Earth cross-section showing location of the Mohorovi<U+010D>i<U+0107> discontinuity (labelled as 2)]]
[[File:Refraction of P-wave.PNG|thumb|250px|Two paths of a ''P''-wave, one direct and one refracted as it crosses the Moho.<ref name=McLeish/>]]
[[Image:Gros Morne moho.jpg|right|thumb|250px|[[Ordovician]] [[ophiolite]] in [[Gros Morne National Park]], [[Newfoundland and Labrador|Newfoundland]]. This rock which formed the Ordovician Moho is exposed on the surface.]]

The '''Mohorovi<U+010D>i<U+0107> discontinuity''' {{IPAc-en|m|oh|h|oh|'|r|oh|v|i-|ch|I|ch}} ({{IPA-sh|moxoro<U+028B>it<U+0283>it<U+0255>|lang}}), usually referred to as the '''Moho''', is the [[Core<U+2013>mantle boundary|boundary]] between the [[Earth]]'s [[Crust (geology)|crust]] and the [[Mantle (geology)|mantle]]. Named after the pioneering [[Croats|Croatian]] [[seismologist]] [[Andrija Mohorovi<U+010D>i<U+0107>]], the Moho separates both the [[oceanic crust]] and [[continental crust]] from underlying mantle. The Moho mostly lies entirely within the [[lithosphere]]; only beneath [[mid-ocean ridge]]s does it define the [[lithosphere]] <U+2013> [[asthenosphere]] boundary. The Mohorovi<U+010D>i<U+0107> discontinuity was first identified in 1909 by Mohorovi<U+010D>i<U+0107>, when he observed that [[seismogram]]s from shallow-focus [[earthquake]]s had two sets of [[P-waves|''P''-waves]] and [[S-waves|''S''-waves]], one that followed a direct path near the Earth's surface and the other [[refraction|refracted]] by a high velocity medium.<ref name=McLeish>{{cite book |title=Geological science |author=Andrew McLeish |page=122 |url=http://books.google.com/?id=rhkgwEvrVe8C&pg=PA122 |isbn=0174482213 |year=1992 |edition=2nd |publisher=Thomas Nelson & Sons}}</ref>

The Mohorovi<U+010D>i<U+0107> discontinuity is {{convert|5|to(-)|10|km|mi|sigfig=1}} below the [[ocean floor]] and {{convert|20|to(-)|90|km|mi|sigfig=1}} beneath typical [[continental crust|continents]], with an average of {{convert|35|km|mi}} beneath them.<ref name=Monroe>{{cite book |title=The changing Earth: exploring geology and evolution |author= James Stewart Monroe, Reed Wicander |url=http://books.google.com/?id=jFPMa4MxwJkC&pg=PA216 |page=216 |isbn=0495554804 |edition=5th |publisher=Cengage Learning |year=2008}}</ref>

==Nature==
Immediately above the Moho the velocities of primary seismic waves (''P''-waves) are synonymous with those through [[basalt]] (6.7 <U+2013> 7.2&nbsp;km/s), and below they are similar to that of [[Peridotite|peridotitic]] or [[Dunite|dunitic]] (7.6 <U+2013> 8.6&nbsp;km/s).<ref name=Badescu>{{cite book |title=Macro-engineering: a challenge for the future |page=169 |author=RB Cathcart & MM <U+0106>irkovi<U+0107> |editor=Viorel Badescu, Richard Brook Cathcart, Roelof D. Schuiling |url=http://books.google.com/?id=5bZBEM31K1MC&pg=PA169 |isbn=1402037392 |year=2006 |publisher=Springer}}</ref> That suggests the Moho marks a change of composition, but the interface appears to be too even for any believable sorting mechanism within the Earth. Near-surface observations suggest such sorting produces an irregular surface.<ref name=Howell>{{cite book |title=An introduction to seismological research: history and development |author=Benjamin Franklin Howell |url=http://books.google.com/?id=3LSW6xQxr0kC&pg=PA77 |page=77 ''ff'' |isbn=0521385717 |year=1990 |publisher=Cambridge University Press}}</ref>

==Exploration==
During the late 1950s and early 1960s, a proposal was taken up in the executive committee of the U.S. [[National Science Foundation]] to drill a hole through the ocean floor to reach this boundary. However the operation, named [[Project Mohole]], never received sufficient support and was mismanaged; it was canceled by the [[United States Congress]] in 1967. Simultaneous efforts were made by the Soviet Union at the [[Kola Superdeep Borehole|Kola Institute]], which reached a depth of {{convert|12260|m|ft}} over 15 years, the world's deepest hole [[Sakhalin-I#World_record_wells|until 2011]], before that attempt was also abandoned in 1989.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wired.com/science/discoveries/multimedia/2008/08/gallery_kola_borehole |title=How the Soviets Drilled the Deepest Hole in the World |work=Wired |date=2008-08-25 |accessdate=2008-08-26}}</ref> 

Reaching the discontinuity remains an important scientific objective. A more recent proposal considers a self-descending tungsten capsule heated by radiogenic heat to explore [[Structure of the Earth|Earth's interior]] near the Moho discontinuity and in the upper mantle.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Ozhovan |first=M. |coauthors=F. Gibb, P. Poluektov and E. Emets |year=2005 |month=August |title=Probing of the Interior Layers of the Earth with Self-Sinking Capsules |journal=Atomic Energy |volume=99 |issue=2 |pages=556<U+2013>562 |doi=10.1007/s10512-005-0246-y}}</ref> The Japanese project [[Chikyu Hakken]] ("Earth Discovery") also aims to explore this general area.

